docs.abstract: For decades, dominance in the technology industry was based on software or hardware. Now it is increasingly based on who owns the best data.
docs.snippet: For decades, dominance in the technology industry was based on software or hardware. Now it is increasingly based on who owns the best data.
docs.lead_paragraph: Wealth and influence in the technology business have always been about gaining the upper hand in software or the machines that software ran on.

headline.main: Data Could Be the Next Tech Hot Button for Regulators

docs.abstract: Microsoft, Facebook, Google and Amazon used their PACs to support Republican Congressional candidates more than Democratic ones in 2016.
docs.snippet: Microsoft, Facebook, Google and Amazon used their PACs to support Republican Congressional candidates more than Democratic ones in 2016.
docs.lead_paragraph: In 2016, the corporate PACs associated with Microsoft, Facebook, Google and Amazon broke ranks with the traditional allegiance of the broad tech sector to the Democratic Party. All four donated more money to Republican Congressional candidates than they did to their Democratic opponents.

headline.main: Silicon Valley Takes a Right Turn

docs.abstract: A slew of major American companies prominently featured everyday Muslim men, women and children in their marketing last year.
docs.snippet: A slew of major American companies prominently featured everyday Muslim men, women and children in their marketing last year.
docs.lead_paragraph: The gentle piano music starts as the doorbell chimes. A white-haired Christian pastor greets his friend, a Muslim imam, and the two converse and laugh over a cup of tea, wincing about their creaky knees as they prepare to part ways. Later, it spurs the same idea in each for a gift: kneepads sent via Amazon Prime. (It is a commercial, after all.)

headline.main: In Year of Anti-Muslim Vitriol, Brands Promote Inclusion
headline.print_headline: In Year of Anti-Muslim Vitriol, Promoting Inclusion

docs.abstract: Giant tech companies are usually challenged by start-ups. But with no obvious upstart competitors, it may be governments that pose the biggest threat.
docs.snippet: Giant tech companies are usually challenged by start-ups. But with no obvious upstart competitors, it may be governments that pose the biggest threat.
docs.lead_paragraph: In the technology industry, the sharks have never long been safe from the minnows. Over much of the last 40 years, the biggest players in tech — from IBM to Hewlett-Packard to Cisco to Yahoo — were eventually outmaneuvered by start-ups that came out of nowhere.

headline.main: Tech Giants Seem Invincible. That Worries Lawmakers.
